# SOP: Configure Apache HTTPD Logs to AWS CloudWatch Logs Using Amazon CloudWatch Agent

## Objective

Configure an Amazon Linux 2 EC2 instance to send Apache HTTPD Access Logs and Error Logs to AWS CloudWatch Log Groups.

---

# Step 1: Launch EC2 Instance

* Launch an Amazon Linux 2 EC2 instance.
* Allow the following inbound ports in the Security Group:

  * SSH (22)
  * HTTP (80)

---

# Step 2: Update the Server

```bash
sudo yum update -y
```

---

# Step 3: Install Apache HTTP Server

```bash
sudo yum install httpd -y
```

Start Apache Service

```bash
sudo systemctl start httpd
```

Enable Apache Service

```bash
sudo systemctl enable httpd
```

Verify Apache Status

```bash
sudo systemctl status httpd
```

---

# Step 4: Deploy Sample Application

Create an HTML page

```bash
sudo vi /var/www/html/index.html
```

Example Content

```html
<html>
<head>
<title>CloudWatch Demo</title>
</head>
<body>
<h1>Apache HTTPD Server</h1>
<h2>CloudWatch Agent Demo</h2>
</body>
</html>
```

Restart Apache

```bash
sudo systemctl restart httpd
```

Verify

```text
http://<EC2-Public-IP>
```

---

# Step 5: Create IAM Role

Create an IAM Role with:

Trusted Entity

* EC2

Attach Policy

```
CloudWatchAgentServerPolicy
```

Attach the IAM Role to the EC2 Instance.

Verify IAM Role

```bash
curl http://169.254.169.254/latest/meta-data/iam/security-credentials/
```

You should see your IAM Role name.

---

# Step 6: Install AWS CloudWatch Agent

```bash
sudo yum install amazon-cloudwatch-agent -y
```

Verify Installation

```bash
rpm -qa | grep amazon-cloudwatch-agent
```

---

# Step 7: Create CloudWatch Agent Configuration File

```bash
sudo vi /opt/aws/amazon-cloudwatch-agent/etc/amazon-cloudwatch-agent.json
```

Paste the following JSON

```json
{
  "logs": {
    "logs_collected": {
      "files": {
        "collect_list": [
          {
            "file_path": "/var/log/httpd/access_log",
            "log_group_name": "/apache/access-log",
            "log_stream_name": "{instance_id}",
            "timezone": "UTC"
          },
          {
            "file_path": "/var/log/httpd/error_log",
            "log_group_name": "/apache/error-log",
            "log_stream_name": "{instance_id}",
            "timezone": "UTC"
          }
        ]
      }
    }
  }
}
```

Save the file.

---

# Step 8: Start CloudWatch Agent

```bash
sudo /opt/aws/amazon-cloudwatch-agent/bin/amazon-cloudwatch-agent-ctl \
-a fetch-config \
-m ec2 \
-c file:/opt/aws/amazon-cloudwatch-agent/etc/amazon-cloudwatch-agent.json \
-s
```

---

# Step 9: Verify CloudWatch Agent Status

```bash
sudo systemctl status amazon-cloudwatch-agent
```

---

# Step 10: Verify Agent Logs

```bash
tail -f /opt/aws/amazon-cloudwatch-agent/logs/amazon-cloudwatch-agent.log
```

Expected Output

```
piping log from /apache/access-log

piping log from /apache/error-log
```

---

# Step 11: Verify Apache Logs

Access Log

```bash
tail -f /var/log/httpd/access_log
```

Error Log

```bash
tail -f /var/log/httpd/error_log
```

---

# Step 12: Generate Traffic

Open Browser

```
http://<EC2-Public-IP>
```

Or

```bash
curl http://localhost
```

Refresh the page multiple times.

---

# Step 13: Verify CloudWatch Log Groups

AWS Console

CloudWatch

↓

Log Groups

You should see

```
/apache/access-log

/apache/error-log
```

---

# Step 14: Verify Log Streams

Open

```
/apache/access-log
```

Select the Log Stream

Verify Access Logs

Repeat the same for

```
/apache/error-log
```

---

# Step 15: Generate Error Logs

Open

```
http://<EC2-Public-IP>/test
```

You should receive

```
404 Not Found
```

Verify the logs in

```bash
tail -f /var/log/httpd/error_log
```

and

CloudWatch Log Group

```
/apache/error-log
```

---

# Step 16: Useful Verification Commands

Check Apache

```bash
sudo systemctl status httpd
```

Restart Apache

```bash
sudo systemctl restart httpd
```

Check CloudWatch Agent

```bash
sudo systemctl status amazon-cloudwatch-agent
```

Restart CloudWatch Agent

```bash
sudo systemctl restart amazon-cloudwatch-agent
```

Verify IAM Role

```bash
curl http://169.254.169.254/latest/meta-data/iam/security-credentials/
```

List CloudWatch Log Groups

```bash
aws logs describe-log-groups --region us-east-1
```

View Agent Logs

```bash
tail -f /opt/aws/amazon-cloudwatch-agent/logs/amazon-cloudwatch-agent.log
```

View Apache Access Logs

```bash
tail -f /var/log/httpd/access_log
```

View Apache Error Logs

```bash
tail -f /var/log/httpd/error_log
```

---

# Outcome

* Apache HTTPD installed successfully.
* Sample application hosted.
* IAM Role attached to EC2.
* Amazon CloudWatch Agent installed and configured.
* Apache Access Logs streamed to `/apache/access-log`.
* Apache Error Logs streamed to `/apache/error-log`.
* Logs successfully viewed in AWS CloudWatch Console.
* Centralized logging implemented for monitoring and troubleshooting.
